# Building a Single‑File EXE (No Installer) for .NET Windows Forms

This guide explains how to publish a .NET Windows Forms application as a **single, self‑contained executable** (no installer) and **digitally sign** it with a code‑signing certificate. The result is a single `.exe` file that users can run immediately—no .NET runtime installation required.

---

## 📋 Prerequisites

- [.NET SDK](https://dotnet.microsoft.com/download) (6.0 or later recommended)
- Windows 10/11 SDK (for `signtool.exe`) – install via Visual Studio Installer or from [Windows SDK](https://developer.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/downloads/windows-sdk/)
- A code‑signing certificate in `.pfx` format (with or without password)
- Windows OS (the signing tools are Windows‑only)

---

## 🛠️ Building a Single‑File Executable (Command Line)

### 1. Using Command Prompt or PowerShell

Open a **Command Prompt** or **PowerShell** window in your project folder.

```bat
:: Clean previous output (optional)
rmdir /s /q publish_signed 2>nul

:: Publish as a single, self-contained executable for win-x64
dotnet publish YourProject.csproj -c Release -r win-x64 --self-contained true ^
  -p:PublishSingleFile=true ^
  -p:DebugType=None ^
  -p:DebugSymbols=false ^
  -o publish_signed
```

**Explanation of parameters:**
- `-c Release` – build in Release configuration.
- `-r win-x64` – target 64‑bit Windows.
- `--self-contained true` – bundle the .NET runtime with your app.
- `-p:PublishSingleFile=true` – produce a single executable.
- `-p:DebugType=None -p:DebugSymbols=false` – exclude debug symbols.
- `-o publish_signed` – output directory.

After the command succeeds, your single `.exe` will be in `publish_signed\YourAppName.exe`. You can delete any leftover `.pdb` files:

```bat
del /q publish_signed\*.pdb 2>nul
```

### 2. Using Git Bash (Important)

In **Git Bash**, do **not** use the `/p:` syntax because the slash can interfere with MSBuild argument parsing. Use `-p:` instead (with a hyphen).

```bash
dotnet publish ./YourProject.csproj -c Release -r win-x64 --self-contained true \
  -p:PublishSingleFile=true -p:DebugType=None -p:DebugSymbols=false \
  -o publish_signed
```

