## 🔏 Code Signing the Executable

### Locate `signtool.exe`

`signtool` is part of the Windows SDK. Typical paths:
- `C:\Program Files (x86)\Windows Kits\10\bin\10.0.22621.0\x64\signtool.exe`
- `C:\Program Files (x86)\Windows Kits\10\bin\10.0.22000.0\x64\signtool.exe`

You can also use `where signtool` in **Command Prompt** to find it.

### Sign with a PFX Certificate

Set the paths to your certificate and the executable, then run `signtool`:

```bat
set PFX=C:\path\to\your\certificate.pfx
set EXE=C:\path\to\publish_signed\YourAppName.exe

signtool sign /f "%PFX%" /fd SHA256 /tr http://timestamp.digicert.com /td SHA256 "%EXE%"
```

- `/f` – path to the `.pfx` file.
- `/fd SHA256` – file digest algorithm.
- `/tr <URL>` – RFC 3161 timestamp server (adds a trusted timestamp).
- `/td SHA256` – digest algorithm for the timestamp.

If your `.pfx` has a password, add `/p YourPassword`. If the password is empty (uncommon), you can try `/p ""`:

```bat
signtool sign /f "%PFX%" /p "" /fd SHA256 /tr http://timestamp.digicert.com /td SHA256 "%EXE%"
```

### Verify the Signature

After signing, verify that the signature is valid:

```bat
signtool verify /pa /v "%EXE%"
```

- `/pa` – verify using the Authenticode policy.
- `/v` – verbose output.

