## 🔁 Integrating into Visual Studio (Post‑Build Event)

You can automate the entire process (publish + sign) in Visual Studio so that every **Release** build produces a signed single‑file executable.

1. Open your project properties.
2. Go to **Build Events** → **Post‑build event command line**.
3. Paste the following script (adjust paths to `signtool.exe` and your `.pfx`):

```bat
if /I "$(ConfigurationName)"=="Release" (
  call dotnet publish "$(ProjectPath)" -c Release -r win-x64 --self-contained true ^
    -p:PublishSingleFile=true -p:DebugType=None -p:DebugSymbols=false ^
    -o "$(ProjectDir)publish_signed"

  del /q "$(ProjectDir)publish_signed\*.pdb" 2>nul

  call "C:\Program Files (x86)\Windows Kits\10\bin\10.0.22621.0\x64\signtool.exe" sign ^
    /f "C:\path\to\your\certificate.pfx" /fd SHA256 /tr http://timestamp.digicert.com /td SHA256 ^
    "$(ProjectDir)publish_signed\$(AssemblyName).exe"

  call "C:\Program Files (x86)\Windows Kits\10\bin\10.0.22621.0\x64\signtool.exe" verify /pa /v ^
    "$(ProjectDir)publish_signed\$(AssemblyName).exe"
)
```

**What it does:**
- Runs only in **Release** configuration.
- Publishes the project as a single self‑contained EXE.
- Deletes any leftover `.pdb` files.
- Signs the generated EXE with your certificate.
- Verifies the signature (optional, you can remove the `verify` line).

After a successful build, your signed executable will be in:
```
$(ProjectDir)publish_signed\$(AssemblyName).exe
```

